reviewText: ...of this DVD.  I just watched this in the stereo format (There is 5.1 too, which I will play soon) and was impressed, not only with the sound, but the set list.  The 4:3 video transfer is very good and does not look stretched when my TV is set to wide for the picture.This 79 minute set occurred in 1994, not long after the tribute to Muddy Waters album, with the blues humming through the air.  This DVD is way more than a Paul Rodgers back catalog of favorites (See set list below).  There is not just the Free or Bad Company feel to the sound.  There is a great compilation of Blues based songs, with band mates that blaze through the set list.A few stand-outs are Muddy Water Blues and Good Morning Little School Girl, with Brian May on guitar, being just one of the friends.  There are many "Friends" on this disc and plenty of guitar solos.  We see some Blues Greats sitting in on the last song Hoochie Coochie Man.The band and friends are Queen guitarist Brian May, drummer Jason Bonham, Steve Lukather from Toto, and Journey guitarist Neal Schon. Guitarist Ian Hatton, bassist John Smithson and such blues performers and players as Eddie Kirkland, Sherman Robertson, Luther Allison, Robert Lucas and Kenny Neal also appear.Track Listing:1) Introduction2) Travelling Man3) Wishing Well4) Louisiana Blues5) Fire And Water6) Muddy Water Blues7) Good Morning Little School Girl8) I'm Ready9) Little Bit Of Love10) Mr. Big11) Feel Like Making Love12) Let Me Love You Baby13) The Hunter14) Can't Get Enough15) All Right Now16) Crossroads17) Hoochie Coochie ManHighly recommended.  Hope this helps.  j
